  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions or legitimate businesses. Key legal elements typically include:\n\n1. Basic legal definition:\n- Concealing the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Transforming \"dirty\" money into seemingly \"clean\" money\n- Disguising the origin of criminal proceeds\n\n2. Common legal elements:\n- Intentional financial transactions\n- Knowledge that funds are derived from criminal activity\n- Attempting to make illegal funds appear legitimate\n\n3. Typical stages of money laundering:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (concealing original source through complex transactions)\n- Integration (reintroducing funds as seemingly legitimate income)\n\n4. Jurisdictional variations exist, but most definitions involve:\n- Criminal intent\n- Financial transactions\n- Proceeds from specific unlawful activities\n\n5. Common predicate crimes often include:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Organized crime activities\n\nNote: Specific legal definitions can vary by country and jurisdiction. This provides a general overview of common legal interpretations.",
